<p>When enabling the “Block command line pushes that expose my email” feature, you’ll also want to configure Git to use your no-reply email address. Don’t worry—this won’t affect your contribution graph. All commits will still be associated with your account.</p>

<ul>
  <li>Open Terminal.</li>
  <li>Change the current working directory to the local repository where you want to configure the email address that you associate with your Git commits.</li>
  <li>Find your GitHub noreply address in your GitHub’s <a href="https://github.com/settings/emails">Personal Settings &gt; Emails</a>. It’s mentioned in the description of the Keep my email address private checkbox. Usually, it starts with a unique identifier, plus your username.</li>
  <li>Set an email address in Git. Use your GitHub-provided no-reply email address.</li>
  <li>Setting your email address for every repository on your computer</li>
  <li>git config <code class="highlighter-rouge">--global user.email "{ID}+{username}@users.noreply.github.com"</code></li>
  <li>Setting your email address for a single repository
    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git config user.email "{ID}+{username}@users.noreply.github.com"
</code></pre></div>    </div>
    <p>Reset the author information on your last commit:</p>
    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git commit --amend --reset-author
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>If you have multiple commits with your private e-mail address, see this answer.
